-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: British American of Kenya, First Bank
-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 2012-01-11T15:24:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-11/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-british-american-of-kenya-first-bank.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  rose for a
fifth day, gaining 0.6 percent to 55.72 in Nairobi, the longest
rally since the five days through May 6.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  declined for a third day, falling
0.4 percent to 1,877.66 by the end of trading. The  FTSE/Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  retreated 0.5 percent to 869.04 in Windhoek. The
 Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX)  weakened 0.1 percent to
20,878.71 at the close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed
statement from the bourse.  The following shares were active in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  British-American Investment Co. (BRIT)  (BRIT KN), a Kenyan
financial services group, slumped 4 percent to 4.8 shillings,
the lowest close since Dec. 20, after it warned that full-year
profit may decline at least 25 percent after the value of its
equity portfolio dropped.  First Bank of Nigeria Plc  (FIRSTBAN NL), Nigeria’s third-
largest lender by market value, fell for a third day, retreating
1.2 percent to 8.84 naira, the lowest close since Jan. 4. Banks
in Nigeria were shut as a general strike to protest the removal
of fuel subsidies continued for a third day.  Zenith Bank Plc (ZENITHBA)  , the West African nation’s
second-biggest bank, weakened 1.2 percent to 12.15 naira.  First
City Monument Bank Plc (FCMB)  , dropped 4.6 percent to 3.91
naira, the lowest close in a month.  Sterling Bank Plc (STERLNBA)  , declined 4.1 percent to 93 kobo, the lowest since at least
2006, when Bloomberg began tracking the stock.  To contact the reporter on this story:
